<HEAD>Legislators Block Federal Spending For Shopping Center Roads</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal money cannot be used to construct
roads for a shopping center being built adjacent to a historic
Civil War battlefield, lawmakers agreed Friday.
   Members of a House and Senate conference committee adopted a
measure introduced by Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., that prohibits
federal funds from being used for the planning, design, or approval
of an interchange near the proposed William Center development,
about 27 miles west of the nation's capital.
   The conference committee is seeking to reconcile House and
Senate versions of a $10.8 billion transportation appropriations
bill.
   The measure, which was included the appropriations bill, will
expire in two years, but Mrazek said it could be renewed if a
dispute between the shopping center developer and preservationists
is not resolved by then.
   ``The result today makes it manifestly clear that the Congress
does not want to assist in the development of this land,'' said
Mrazek, who predicted that a ``substantial amount'' of the
development tract would ultimately be saved.
   The 542-acre development is adjacent to the Manassas National
Battlefield Park, site of two crucial Civil War battles.
   Historians argue that the project, which would include a 1.2
million square-foot shopping mall, 1.7 million square feet of
office space and 560 homes, would destroy the rustic sanctity of
the 4,200-acre park.
   Sen. John Warner, R-Va., is preparing legislation that would
seize a section of the site and direct the developer, John T.
Hazel, to eliminate the shopping mall from his plans and greatly
reduce the amount of office space.
   Warner's plan would add to the park a hill from which
Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee commanded his troops during the
Second Battle of Manassas. Historians and preservationists argue
that this parcel is the most significant in the entire development
tract.
   Transporation officials have estimated that the interchange
would cost up to $50 million.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

