<HEAD>Suburban Sprawl Threatens Famed Battlefield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A third battle of Manassas is brewing, this
one over a shopping center complex being built near where the Union
and Rebel forces clashed in 1861 and again in 1862.
   Neither the outrage of preservationists, the pleas of Civil War
buffs nor 166 signatures on congressional legislation has been able
to stop bulldozers from plowing ground on the project.
   Construction crews already have begun to lay access roads and
prepare the property for sewers. They expect to start construction
on the first section of 560 townhouses and detached homes in 60
days.
   The developers say the section is not part of the land
considered sacred by historians. But local preservationists argue
that even if the hill from which Confederate Gen. Robert E. Lee
directed troops has not yet been touched, the excavation work
should stop until Congress has had time to act.
   The National Manassas Battlefield, about 30 miles from
Washington, is cherished for its bucolic surroundings where
visitors can easily imagine what Civil War troops saw in 1861 and
1862 during two of the South's important victories _ the battles of
Manassas, or as Northerners say, the battles of Bull Run.
   But the Washington metropolitan area is one of the nation's
fastest growing regions, and any land around the 4,500-acre
historic park not owned by the government is vulnerable to
surburban sprawl.
   As for the 600 acres adjacent to the park where Lee's troops
gathered and battlefield hospitals were located, Hazel-Peterson Co.
plans to go ahead with construction unless stopped by Congress,
said Robert C. Kelly, spokesman for the firm, the most prominent
development company in northern Virginia.
   A few weeks ago, Reps. Robert Mzarek, D-N.Y., and Michael
Andrews, D-Texas, started action to stop construction by
introducing a bill that would have the interior secretary take
possession of the land for park expansion.
   It quickly got the approval of at least 166 members of the House
who signed on as co-sponsors, but did not win over the three
congressmen whose districts comprise northern Virginia. All are
Republicans and all are well-acquainted with the wealthy Hazel
family and its involvement in local GOP politics.
   In fact, not one of Virginia's 10 members of Congress had signed
on in support of the Mzarek-Andrews bill or entered into the debate
in any way.
   Last week, that changed and suddenly there was new hope for
historians that the bulldozers would be idled.
   Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., whose district is near the battlefield,
introduced a bill that would enable the government to acquire the
land through ``legislative taking,'' a process that is faster than
that proposed by Mzarek and Andrews. Wolf's bill also provides for
highway construction to relieve traffic congestion threatening the
park.
   Mzarek and Andrews quickly gave their support for the plan, and
immediately signing on as a co-sponsor was Rep. Stan Parris, R-Va.,
a longtime friend and partner in some business ventures with John
``Til'' Hazel, who runs Hazel-Peterson Co.
   Supporting development are county officials who anticipate
increased tax revenues.
   ``We are pleased and happy the project is being built,'' said
Robert Noe, Prince William County executive before Wolf introduced
his bill. ``The greatest hope for stability in the tax base is
economic development and a regional mall is the catalyst for the
kind of economic development communities need.''
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel also has opposed congressional
intervention, saying the land would cost the government too much.
   Hazel-Peterson spokesman Kelly said his firm bought the land for
between $10 million and $12 million. Hodel said it probably would
cost the government $70 million to acquire it.
   ``Not only is the cost high, but it will not solve the problem,
since the proposed mall could simply move further down the road,
either imposing a traffic burden on the park or requiring that land
also to be purchased,'' said Hodel in a letter to Rep. Morris
Udall, D-Ariz., chairman of the House Interior Committee.
   ``Development is going to occur all around the battlefield
whether it is us or someone else,'' said Kelly. ``This land is not
for sale. We don't want it taken and we are proceeding with
construction.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>

