<HEAD>House Panel OKs Seizure of Land Planned for Battlefield Shopping
Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A House subcommittee on Thursday approved a
bill to seize land that was to be used for a disputed shopping
center adjacent to a Civil War battlefield near the nation's
capital.
   The Interior and Insular Affairs subcommittee on national parks
and public lands acted to take control of a 542-acre tract
bordering the Manassas National Battlefield Park, the site of two
major Civil War battles.
   A developer has planned a massive shopping, residential and
office complex next to the 4,600-acre battlefield park located in
Prince William County, Va., 27 miles west of Washington. But
historians and local groups have claimed the development would
destroy the still-rustic sanctity of the park.
   ``This is a remedy the Congress, and the American people, have
available,'' said Rep. Bruce Vento, D-Minn., chairman of the panel.
``I don't see any other alternative to dealing with this problem.''
   The bill, which combines prior measures proposed by Reps. Robert
Mrazek, D-N.Y., and Michael Andrews, D-Texas, and a separate
proposal by Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., also would close U.S. 29 and
state route 234, which run through the park, and provide up to $30
million for the construction of new roads around the site. The
federal government also would pay the site's developer, the
Hazel-Peterson Cos., for the land that was seized.
   The land was sold to developer John T. Hazel for an estimated
$12 million in 1985. Land experts estimate repurchasing the land
and paying for road closings could cost the government up to $150
million.
   ``We will eventually pay probably three times what we have spent
in the past year on acquisitions for national parks,'' said Rep.
Ron Marlenee, R-Mont. ``Oh, for the shame of taxpayer abuse we have
in this legislation.''
   He said the roads in the park should be closed, but the
development plans should be allowed to proceed.
   The bill now moves to the full Interior committee, which is
chaired by Rep. Morris Udall, D-Ariz.
   On Wednesday, the House passed a transportation bill that
included an amendment offered by Mrazek that would prevent federal
involvement in the costly construction of bypasses or access roads
associated with the development.
   Hazel plans to build a complex featuring 1.2 million square-feet
of retail space, 1.7 million square-feet of office space and 560
homes.
   The development site is next to the area in which the First and
Second Battles of Manassas were fought.
</TEXT>
