<HEAD>House Bill Bans Road Funds for Shopping Center Near Civil War Site</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Mrazek's first name to Robert sted Jerome in 4th
graf, ``This is''</NOTE>
<TEXT>
   By RICHARD KEIL=
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The House on Wednesday approved a measure
prohibiting federal involvement in road projects for a disputed
shopping center scheduled to be built next to a Civil War
battlefield in northern Virginia.
   The provision, included in a $10.8 billion transportation bill
approved by the House, prevents federal money from being used for
the planning, design or construction of bypasses or access roads
associated with the William Center development just west of
Washington in Prince William County, Va.
   The development is being opposed by local groups who say it
would be detrimental to the adjacent Manassas National Battlefield
Park.
   ``This is designed to indicate Congress' interest in this piece
of land,'' said Tad Boggs, an aide to Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y.,
who sponsored the provision. ``This is a shot across the
developer's bow, and is intended to buy us time until we come up
with a plan to purchase the land.''
   The bill is the first piece of legislation passed by the House
that attempts to stop the 542-acre development, which historians
claim would violate the sanctity of the 4,600-acre park where two
major Civil War battles were fought.
   The project's developers have offered to help pay for road
construction, but federal funds usually are needed for a project of
this size to be completed. Mrazek's provision prohibits federal
involvement in road bypasses or alterations associated with
Interstate 66, which runs adjacent to the park, and U.S. 29 and
state route 234, which run through the battle site.
   The project, proposed by the Hazel-Peterson Cos., would feature
a 1.2 million-square-foot shopping center, 1.7 million-square-feet
of office space and 560 homes. John T. Hazel, president of the
development group, first proposed a much smaller office park for
the space, but upgraded his plans once county officials relaxed
zoning requirements for the tract.
   Mrazek is a co-sponsor of another House bill that would take
control of the development tract and add it to the boundaries of
the park. That measure is scheduled to be voted on by a House
Interior and Insular Affairs panel Thursday.
</TEXT>
