<HEAD>Indians Urge Monument to Warriors Who Fell at Little Big Horn in
Montana</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 4th graf: ``A memorial,'' to RESTORE dropped words
``would cost about''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American Indian leaders urged Congress on
Tuesday to approve a memorial to the warriors who fell at Little
Big Horn while Virginia officials urged a national commission to
help preserve Civil War battlefields.
   ``We need to honor our warriors who gave their lives,'' Carol
Gipp of the National Congress of American Indians told the House
Interior Committee's subcommittee on national parks and public
lands.
   The appeal came as Indians, conservationists and others crowded
the hearing room to plead for approval of favorite bills before
Congress adjourns next month.
   A memorial to the warriors who fell in the 1876 victory of the
Sioux over Lt. Col. George Custer and a detachment of the 7th
Cavalry Regiment would cost about $2.1 million, the National Park
Service has estimated. The service is supporting the memorial, as
yet undesigned.
   The memorial would be adjacent to the monument to the 7th
Cavalry which was erected on Last Stand Hill on the Montana
battlefield in 1881. It bears the full names of Custer and each of
the 224 other men in his command.
   Custer was a temporary general with the Union Army during the
Civil War but reverted to lieutenant colonel afterward, the rank he
held in 1876.
   Susan Shown-Harjo, president of the Morning Star Foundation
representing the Cheyenne and Arapaho Tribes, said the names of the
cavalry troopers on the monument has given them ``dignity in
death.''
   ``Our people who died there are referred to as hordes of Indians
along with the cavalry who are named,'' she said.
   The number of Indian dead is unknown, but the National Park
Service says no more than 100 are believed to have been killed in
the battle.
   Virginia officials and historic preservationists urged approval
of a national commission on civil war battlefields to help shield a
number of sites from development as the suburbs outside the
nation's capital spread southward.
   Mayor Elizabeth G. Helm of Winchester pointed to estimates that
employment in the Dulles Corridor outside Washington would grow
more than 1,000 percent and the homes of those joining the labor
force most likely would be in central Maryland and the northern
Shenandoah Valley.
   ``This same area is heavily steeped in history and tradition but
we have tended to take this heritage for granted,'' she said. ``We
have assumed that it will always be with us for future
generations.''
   ``Our ancestors provided beautifully for large and splendid
Confederate and national cemeteries but no one anticipated the
growth that has obliterated many of the battlefields,'' she added.
   Also urging action were Reps. Jim Olin, D-Va., and D. French
Slaughter Jr., R-Va., as well as historic preservationists who are
urging quick action by the government before suburban sprawl
gobbles up battlefields.
   Dr. James Gardner, deputy director of the American Historical
Association, however, opposed the plan. If approved, he said,
``greater and greater amounts of money will be pushed into this
aspect of our history to the exclusion of others.''
   He said preservationists ``should not be so preoccupied with
Civil War battlefields.''
   ``We need to pull back from this Civil War focus and take a
broader view of American history,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

