<HEAD>Report Says No U.S. Protest Filed Over Rifle Sales</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A congressional report says the United States
never lodged an official protest with South Korea over evidence
that American-designed rifles built in Korea have been sold to
foreign countries in violation of a U.S.-Korean agreement.
   The General Accounting Office found there was little oversight
of the program and confusion over which government agency should be
in charge of the 1971 pact, which banned sales of the M-16 rifles
to foreign nations without U.S. permission and placed a cap on the
number South Korea could produce.
   ``Defense and State Department officials in various agencies and
locations told us that they were not responsible for managing the
program,'' said the report, which was obtained Wednesday by The
Associated Press.
   When presented with evidence of illegal foreign sales, the State
Department usually instructed embassy officials to remind Korea of
the ``seriousness'' of such sales. A strong, official government
protest was never lodged, GAO said.
   The agreement included Colt Industries Firearms Division of
Hartford, Conn., which set up the Korean rifle plant in exchange
for per-weapon royalties.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Average Full Professor Now Earns $47,400</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The average full professor at an American
college or university now earns $47,400, according to the American
Association of University Professors.
   The faculty group said Wednesday that its survey of 300,000
professors on 1,900 campuses showed salaries rose by 4.9 percent in
1987-88, compared to a 5.9 percent increase the year before.
   Across all faculty ranks _ including associate professors,
assistant professors, lecturers and instructors _ the average
salary was $37,000.
   The association, which conducts collective bargaining on some
campuses, said that after inflation, faculty salaries rose by just
0.9 percent.
   The association said faculty salaries vary widely by region,
with full professors averaging $52,510 on the West Coast and
Hawaii, and less than $42,000 in some Southern and Central states.
   Salaries rose 5.6 percent at private, independent colleges and
universities, compared with 4.7 percent at public and
church-related campuses.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Congressmen Make Stand Where Union Forces Held Off Confederates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two congressmen are trying to place a
legislative wall in front of a developer's plans to build a
shopping center next to a historic Civil War battlefield.
   A bill introduced Wednesday by Reps. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., and
Michael Andrews, D-Texas, would direct the Interior Department to
purchase from a developer a 600-acre plot of land adjacent to the
Manassas National Battlefield Park, where two important Civil War
battles were fought.
   The congressmen say plans for a 1.2 million square-foot shopping
center would violate the battlefield site.
   ``We've come to this conclusion because both of us feel there's
no other choice,'' said Andrews. ``Both of us are convinced that
the local developers and politicians intend to build the shopping
mall.''
   The 3,800-acre Manassas battlefield, about 27 miles west of
Washington, was the site of the first significant land battle of
the Civil War in 1861.
   In a second, three-day battle in 1862, 24,000 Union and
Confederate casualties were recorded, as Union forces that had been
as far south as Richmond 60 days earlier were pushed back into the
nation's capital.
</TEXT>
