<HEAD>Patch of Farmland to Join Antietam National Battlefield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Cornfield is partly a barley field now and
there aren't any trees in the North Woods, but both are becoming
federal property more than a century and a quarter after the Blue
and the Grey fought fiercely for them in the Battle of Antietam.
   The Richard King Mellon Foundation and the Conservation Fund
deeded 148 acres of Maryland farmland, including the two Civil War
sites, to the Interior Department on Monday as part of what was
billed as the largest-ever land donation to the government.
   The farm near Antietam Creek is one of 10 properties that the
Pittsburgh-based foundation has purchased at a cost of more than
$21 million for donation to the government by way of the
Conservation Fund, a land and water conservation organization.
   Also handed over on Monday were 93,000 acres of wildlife habitat
in North Carolina. The tract between Albemarle and Pamlico sounds
will be administered by the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service.
   Gifts scheduled for transfer later in the year are:
   Five Forks at Dinwiddie, Va., site of a battle known as the
Waterloo of the Confederacy; Forked Lightning Ranch, N.M.,
surrounding the Pecos National Monument; 130 acres of upland
adjoining the marshes and open water of Mackay Island National
Wildlife Refuge, N.C.; a 122-acre addition to the Rachel Carson
National Wildlife Refuge, Maine.
   Also, two tracts totaling 468 acres to be added to Rocky
Mountain National Park, Colo.; two parcels of land on and near
Skyline Drive in Shenandoah National Park, Va.; and a 135-acre
addition to the Wilderness Area of Fredericksburg and Spotsylvania
Memorial National Military Park, Va.
   The Antietam farm contained a 30-acre cornfield when the Battle
of Antietam, the bloodiest single day of fighting in American
history, was fought on Sept. 17, 1862. Of the 23,000 killed and
wounded, 55 percent were struck in and around the Cornfield, as the
site became known.
   Some were buried there, said Edwin C. Bearss, chief historian of
the National Park Service. From 1865 to 1867, the dead were removed
to a Union cemetery in Sharpsburg, Md., and to Confederate burial
places in Shepherdstown, W.Va., and Hagerstown, Md.
   The foundation bought the property from Paul Culler, who, with
his son Lynn, has farmed it for 37 years. They plant it in corn
some years and in barley, oats and hay at other times, in
accordance with modern crop rotation. This year, said Lynn Culler,
they have 18 acres in corn and the rest in barley.
   Richard Rambur, superintendent of Antietam National Battlefield
in Sharpsburg, said the Cornfield would be returned to its original
size and configuration on the basis of contemporary maps. He said
trees would be planted in the woods from which Union troops
advanced into the field.
   The Cullers will continue to farm the property for three or four
years under a lease arrangement with the Park Service, as
guaranteed by their arrangement with the Conservation Fund, Rambur
said. After that, it will be put up for lease by the highest
bidder, like other farmland in national parks.
   The farm includes not only the Cornfield, but most of the North
Woods, the wood lot from which Union troops advanced into the tall
corn. There are no trees in the North Woods now, and Rambur said
trees will be planted to make it the way it was in 1862.
   In addition to the farm, the foundation bought two other pieces
of property, outside the park boundary, that will be held for
possible donation later. Altogether, the 280 acres of land sold for
$1.1 million, Conservation Fund spokesman Jack Lynn said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

