<CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Mercury News File Photograph; There are several ways to tour
Gettysburg National Military Park  </CAPTION>
<DESCRIPT>  TRAVEL; PAST; US; WAR; HISTORY; NAME; LIST  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  THE overwhelming success of the "Civil War" television series on PBS last
winter has heightened interest in visiting Civil War battle sites.
Fortunately, most of the states in which the bulk of the Civil War action took
place guard their heritage zealously, and both public and private
organizations are well equipped to help a traveler relive events that took
place more than a century ago.;    What follows is a state-by-state list of
those groups that can assist in fashioning a visit to Civil War battlefields
and related areas.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Travel  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  A BATTLE-TORN NATION
ROAM WHERE AMERICAN CIVIL WAR BATTLES RAGED  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  Consumer  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     (box) PENNSYLVANIA: Gettysburg National Military Park would probably be
paramount on any Civil War buff's itinerary, for the Battle of Gettysburg (in
July of 1863) marked the turning point of the Civil War. The battlefield,
immortalized by Lincoln's Gettysburg Address, is preserved by the National
Park Service, and there are a few ways to tour the area.;    (check) A
self-guided, 18-mile auto tour, using a brochure and map provided at the
Visitor Center; takes about three hours.;    (check) A licensed battlefield
guide can provide a two-hour guided tour in the visitor's car for $20.;   
(check) Bus tours of the battlefield are offered by Gettysburg Tours, 778
Baltimore St., Gettysburg, Pa. 17325; (717) 334-6296. Prices are $9.75 for
adults and $6.55 for children over 5.;    (check) A descriptive auto tape tour
and cassette player can be rented for $10.50. These are available through the
National Civil War Wax Museum, (717) 334-6245.;    A major annual event in
Gettysburg is the Gettysburg Civil War Heritage Days (June 29-July 7).;   
(box) VIRGINIA: More than half of the tragedy that was the Civil War unfolded
in the state of Virginia, from the first major battle at Bull Run (first
Manassas) to Gen. Lee's surrender four years later at Appomattox Court House.;
   The Virginia Division of Tourism -- 1021 E. Cary St., Richmond, Va. 23219;
(804) 786-4484 -- offers an excellent booklet called "Virginia Civil War
Battlefields &amp; Sites," which provides historical background and information on
numerous Civil War sites. The Virginia Division of Tourism can also furnish
information on Civil War-related events taking place in the state this year.; 
  The Fredericksburg Department of Tourism -- 706 Caroline St.,
Fredericksburg, Va. 22401; (703) 373-1776 or (800) 678-4748 -- has a variety
of brochures on the area's sites of historic interest.;    The Richmond
Convention &amp; Visitors Bureau -- 300 E. Main St., Richmond, Va. 23219; (804)
782-2777 -- can provide a list of battlefield locations in the area. Guided
tours are available through Historic Richmond Foundation Tours -- 2407 E.
Grace St., Richmond, Va. 23223; (804) 780-0107. Another tour company, Living
History Associates -- P.O. Box 4914, Richmond, Va. 23220; (804) 353-8166 or
(804) 264-9451 -- offers walking tours, private tours in the visitor's car,
and motor-coach guides for groups, focusing on locations within the city as
well as battlefield sites.;    (box) WEST VIRGINIA: The West Virginia Division
of Tourism &amp; Parks -- 2101 Washington St. E., Charleston, W.Va. 25305; (800)
225-5982 -- has an interesting brochure on Harpers Ferry, site of abolitionist
John Brown's raid on Oct. 16, 1859.;    The Carnifex Ferry Battlefield State
Park -- Route 2, Box 435, Summersville, W.Va. 26651; (304) 872-3773 -- offers
a booklet on the battle at Carnifex Ferry, which took place on Sept. 10, 1861.
They stage a re-enactment of the battle each year, and this year it is
scheduled for Sept. 7 and 8.;    (box) GEORGIA: One of the most dramatic sites
associated with the Civil War was the Andersonville Civil War Prison, where
over 45,000 Union troops were held in a stockade. The village and the prison
-- now commemorated as Andersonville National Historic Site -- are part of
Georgia's Andersonville Trail, a 75-mile sightseeing loop along Interstate 75
between Perry and Cordele. For a brochure and information, contact the Georgia
Department of Industry and Trade, P.O. Box 1776, Atlanta, Ga. 30301; (404)
651-9461.;    The Atlanta History Center -- c/o Atlanta Historical Society,
3101 Andrews Drive N.W., Atlanta, Ga. 30305; (404) 261-1837 -- will be the
site of a presentation called "The Civil War Revisited: Atlanta Encampment
1991," July 20 and 21.;    (box) MARYLAND: The Maryland Office of Tourism --
217 E. Redwood St., Baltimore, Md. 21202; (800) 543-1036 or (301) 333-6611 --
has a brochure called "Maryland Civil War Country," which outlines the major
Civil War sites in Frederick and Washington counties.;    The Maryland Office
of Tourism can also provide a list of historical re-enactments that will take
place in the state this year.;    (box) NORTH CAROLINA: A brochure called
"North Carolina Historic Sites" is offered by the Department of Cultural
Resources, Historic Sites Section, 109 E. Jones St., Raleigh, N.C. 27601;
(919) 733-7862.;    (box) SOUTH CAROLINA: Although few Civil War battles were
fought in South Carolina, the state played a leading role in the war. It was
the first state to secede from the Union, and the first shot of the war was
fired at Fort Sumter in Charleston Harbor. The fort, which fell to the
Confederates in 1861, is now a national monument under the supervision of the
National Park Service, and daily boat tours are available.;    (box)
TENNESSEE: Several items of Civil War-related material are offered by the
Tennessee Tourist Development, P.O. Box 23170, Nashville, Tenn. 37202; (615)
741-2158.;    (box) MISSISSIPPI: The Mississippi Department of Economic
Development -- P.O. Box 849, Jackson, Miss. 39205; (601) 359-3593 -- can
provide information on Civil War sites in its state. Best known is the
National Military Park at Vicksburg, scene of one of the most decisive Union
victories of the war.;    (box) ARKANSAS: One doesn't immediately think of
Arkansas in connection with the Civil War, but several battles took place on
Arkansas soil. Visits can be made to battlefield parks at Prairie Grove, Pea
Ridge, Poison Spring, Marks' Mills, and Jenkins Ferry. Contact the Arkansas
Department of Parks &amp; Tourism, One Capitol Mall, Little Rock, Ark. 72201;
(501) 682-7777.;    (box) LOUISIANA: Port Hudson, La., was the site of the
longest siege in American military history. A brochure on the Port Hudson
battlefield -- which is now a National Historic Landmark -- is available from
the Louisiana Office of Tourism, P.O. Box 94291, Baton Rouge, La. 70804; (504)
342-8119.  </TEXT>
