<HEAD>Senate Won't Pass Bill To Seize Land Adjacent To Battlefield Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GUY DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate won't pass a bill for a
``legislative taking'' of land adjacent to the Manassas National
Battlefield Park in suburban Virginia to prevent the construction
of a shopping center, the chairman of the committee involved said
Wednesday.
   The House passed the bill 307-98 on Aug. 10, taking the 542-acre
Williams Center tract and providing up to $30 million in
compensation. Such a seizure of land is rare and leaves to a later
court determination how much the owner should get.
   Prince William County authorities already have approved the
shopping center, which is to be accompanied by office and
residential development on the tract.
   The controversy has galvanized many environmentalists and Civil
War buffs who see desecration in the location of a shopping center
next to the park commemorating the First and Second Battles of
Manassas in the Civil War.
   Sen. Bennett Johnston, D-La., chairman of the Energy and Natural
Resources Committee, said he intended to vote for the measure and
expected to send it to the floor.
   But the bill violates a Senate rule against bringing
``entitlement'' legislation to the floor outside of the budget
process, and the Budget Committee is unlikely to waive the rule, he
said.
   Sixty senators could vote to set the rule aside, but Johnston
said, ``I frankly don't think it'll pass a 60-vote point of order
at this time in this session.''
   Still, he told his colleagues during a discussion of the bill at
a committee meeting, ``we are at least saying this is a high
priority and this kind of land should not be lost.''
   The ranking Republican, James McClure of Idaho, said the last
``legislative taking,'' a seizure of redwood forest lands in
California in 1980, had been projected to cost $349 million but
would cost $1.4 billion.
   He said land in the Manassas area was now selling for $17 to
$17.50 per square foot, so the entire tract could cost $413 million
at the higher figure.
   McClure noted that the committee had left the tract in private
hands when it enlarged the park in 1980, deciding that it was not
significant enough historically to include in the park.
   ``We made a mistake'' in 1980, said Sen. Dale Bumpers, D-Ark.,
chairman of the national park subcommittee, in arguing for support
of the House bill.
   ``We have a necessity to understand how we got where we are,''
Bumpers said in arguing for the significance of the tract.
   James McPherson, author of the recent highly praised one-volume
history of the Civil War, ``Battle Cry of Freedom,'' testified at a
subcommittee hearing that the Second Battle of Manassas was the
most significant of the war for the South, Bumpers said.
</TEXT>
