<HL> Blood Runs High at Battle of Manassas Mall </HL>
<AUTHOR> Kenneth Smith </AUTHOR>
<SO> </SO>
<IN> REL CON </IN>
<G> CNG </G>
<TEXT>
   Everybody seems to want a piece of Virginia's Prince William County. 
Not just any old piece of this Washington bedroom community will do, however. 
What the media, environmentalists, Civil War groups, citizen activists and lawmakers have their sights set on is prime real estate. 
Never mind that someone else already owns the land in question. 
In hearings scheduled today before the House Subcommittee on National Parks and Public Land, they're backing legislation to seize it. 

   At issue are 542 acres adjacent to Manassas National Battlefield Park, site of two major battles in the War Between the States. 
When the landowner announced earlier this year plans to put a mall, office space and residences on the site -- known as the William Center project -- opponents massed for the latest battle of Manassas. 

   The mall, they said, would be an eyesore, increase traffic and hurt the park's integrity. 
Jonathan Yardley of the Washington Post and Tom Wicker of the New York Times, respectively, wrote paeans to the park's "ethereally beautiful wooded countryside" and warned against the "desecration of hallowed ground." 
Jimmy Carter's former press secretary, Jody Powell, said that because 10 of his ancestors had fought at Manassas he was giving anti-mall forces free P.R. help. 
Congressmen, urged on by mall opponents, jumped in with legislation to take the land. 

   Opposing this federal invasion is a less-celebrated group of citizens and county officials who regard it as unwarranted intrusion into local land-use decisions vital to the county's well-being. 
Prince William's population, now 205,000, is soaring and the county is counting on the expected $87 million in net tax revenues from the William Center in the next 20 years, along with $23 million annually after that, to help pay for services. 
Officials say the number of residents, already up by 50,000 since 1980, will likely increase by 100,000 by 2000. 

   As it is now, the official capacity for the county's school buildings has been exceeded by more than 3,000 students. 
And problems don't stop with education. 
"We have all the fundamental municipal needs, and we cannot continue to finance all those needs on the backs of homeowners," says Kathleen Seefeldt, chairman of the Prince William County Board of Supervisors. 

   What she and other officials fear is creeping federal sovereignty under the guise of preservation. 
The government already controls 20% of the county's land for parks and a Marine base. 
For that sizable chunk the county receives a mere $20,139 annually in lieu of taxes. 
If park borders spread over the mall site, the county will gain a few more dollars in federal contributions but lose millions in taxes. 

   For all the highly publicized opposition, evidence abounds that many residents are more interested in seeing local business rather than the park expand. 
Last year, residents of the district in which the William Center is located elected a pro-economic growth real-estate agent to the Board of Supervisors with 57% of the vote. 
Two area chambers of commerce merged into a single group to support the construction of the mall project. 

   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel has proposed a compromise: The mall could invite increased traffic on two roads now bisecting the park; Mr. Hodel has offered to close the roads, restore them to Civil War condition and replace them with a bypass. 
He also would move the mall to a lower elevation, eliminating its "visual intrusion" on the park. 

   The Board of Supervisors unanimously endorsed the compromise last month but anti-mall forces still want the government to take the land -- at an estimated cost of $70 million to taxpayers. 
For all their professed concern about the park's integrity, many of the residents' true motivations appear to be simply to stop growth. 

   "How long do you think this rural area could survive the influx of all those people who would come with a mall?" asked a leading civic activist. 
Another woman, who moved to the "boondocks" in Prince William 12 years ago, said she had "done nothing but fight" intrusions on that rural atmosphere ever since. 

   In fact, there is no evidence the William Center property actually was a major battlefield. 
A study last year revealed no significant fighting on the site, no historic structures and no soldiers' graves. 
These findings justified, in effect, Congress's decision not to purchase the ground when it last expanded the park in 1980. 

   If preservation arguments prove insufficient, anti-mall forces are ready to try other means. 
Last week they demanded a halt to the project because it could harm wetlands said to be on the site. 

   Says county Supervisor Edwin King, "I have said that most of the people locally who are opposing this {project} would oppose any use of the property with a greater density than a Confederate cemetery. 
That's the basic issue here. 
A lot of those people would have been thrilled if the gates to Prince William County had been locked the day after they arrived." 

   A no-growth agenda is legitimate politics, of course. 
The question is whether Congress wants to sign on to it at the expense of local land-use planning, taxpayers and individual property rights. 

   ---
   Mr. Smith is an editorial writer at the Richmond Times-Dispatch. 

</TEXT>
</DOC>

