<HEAD>Senate Joins Manassas Battlefield Fray</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM SEPPY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When Congress returns from its Labor Day
recess, the Senate will join the controversy over whether a
developer can build a shopping mall adjacent to the famous Civil
War battlefield at Manassas, Va.
   The Senate Energy and Natural Resources subcommittee on public
lands, national parks and forests announced Thursday a hearing will
be held Sept. 8, a day after Congress returns, to consider
legislation directing the federal government to purchase the
542-acre William Center tract adjacent to the Manassas National
Battlefield Park.
   The Confederacy won two battles at Manassas just west of
Washington in 1861 and 1862.
   The subcommittee will hold the hearing on the bill passed by the
House on Wednesday, which orders the federal government to buy the
land.
   Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., who made the announcement of the
hearing, said he will introduce legislation to purchase only part
of the developer's tract. Estimates of the purchase price in the
House bill have ranged from $15 million to $100 million.
   The House bill provides for the federal government to take
immediate ownership of the developer's tract under a rarely used
procedure known as a legislative taking. A fair price for the
developer would be worked out later.
   In addition, the bill authorizes up to $30 million to close two
major highways crossing the park.
   Officials at the Office of Management and Budget and Interior
Department have said they would recommend that President Reagan
veto the measure if Congress enacts it in its current form.
   Developer John T. Hazel purchased the land two years ago for
less than $10 million. He wants to build 1.2 million square feet of
retail space, 1.7 million square feet of office space and 560 homes.
   Opponents contend the development would mar the natural sanctity
of the park.
</TEXT>
