<HEAD>Virginia Congressman Joins Fight To Protect Manassass Battlefield</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Virginia congressman introduced legislation
Wednesday he said would speed congressional efforts to protect the
Manassas National Battlefield from encroaching commercial
development.
   The bill by Rep. Frank Wolf, R-Va., calls for immediate
government acquisition of the approximately 600 acres adjacent to
the park where a developer plans to build a shopping mall.
   It also directs the interior secretary to make sure the scenery
around the park is protected, calls for closing two roads that
bisect the Civil War site and proposes a bypass to carry traffic
around the area.
   A bill already has been introduced for government purchase of
the land now owned by Hazel-Peterson Co. developers, but it directs
acquisition through the Interior Department, a slower process than
the ``legislative taking'' of the land recommended by Wolf.
   The earlier legislation was introduced by Reps. Robert Mrazek,
D-N.Y., and Michael Andrews, D-Texas, and by Wednesday had 166
co-sponsors.
   Tad Boggs, Mrazek's press secretary, said the congressman ``is
wholeheartedly endorsing the (Wolf) bill.''
   ``He hopes that it can be melded together with his bill, but it
accomplishes everything he hopes to see done,'' Boggs said.
   ``I think everyone should be pleased that a Virginian has
finally said no to the shopping mall,'' Andrews said.
   Stan Parris, another Virginia congressman whose district is near
the battlefield just outside Washington, said he will co-sponsor
Wolf's bill.
   Rep. D. French Slaughter Jr., whose district includes the park,
is studying the bill, according to his administrative assistant,
George White.
   Ian Spatz, spokesman for the National Trust for Historic
Preservation, which also has been fighting the developer, said his
organization was encouraged to have Wolf's support.
   ``We want to study it further, but it looks like something we
could support,'' said Spatz. ``(Wolf's plan) provides more
certainty that the property owner would get paid for the property.''
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel had proposed that the developer
move the shopping mall so it would not be visible from the park. He
also said the roads bisecting the park should be closed.
   Though preservationists like the idea of closing the roads, they
say the mall should not be anywhere near the park because of
traffic problems it would create.
</TEXT>
