<HEAD>Warner Vows To Push For Plan To Offset Impact Of Shopping Center</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plan by Sen. John Warner, R-Va., to close
roads through the Manassas National Battlefield Park was killed by
a Senate panel Friday, but Warner vowed to revive the plan in talks
with House members.
   ``I'm going to do my best to try and go forward with planning
roads,'' Warner said after the Senate Appropriations Committee
rejected his request for $2.8 million to study ways to cut off two
heavily traveled roads that run through the historic Civil War
battlefield.
   Warner's compromise plan, which is similar to a previous
Interior Department proposal, is part of a federal effort to reduce
the impact of a proposed 1.2 million square foot shopping center on
the nearby national park.
   Warner does not oppose the commercial complex, but believes that
closing roads within the park would lessen the development's impact
on the battleground.
   Historians and preservationists argue that the complex, which
also would include 1.7 million square feet of office space and 560
homes, would forever violate the sanctity of the still-rustic
battlefield.
   Three measures now under consideration in the House would either
authorize the federal government to purchase the land or scuttle
the shopping center plan by preventing federal highway money from
being used for roads to and from the development.
   Before Warner's plan can again be considered, an amendment that
would prevent federal money from being used for highway
construction associated with the development must be dropped from a
House appropriations bill.
   Congressional rules stipulate that if that amendment, offered by
Rep. Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., Warner's amendment could then be
reconsidered in future talks between House and Senate conferees.
   Mrazek is not likely to drop his amendment, at least until the
outcome of the land-purchase bills is clear, said Tad Boggs, a
spokesman for the congressman.
   Plans to purchase the property offered by Rep. Frank Wolf,
R-Va., and a similar measure by Mrazek and Rep. Michael Andrews,
D-Texas, would also close two roads running through the park and
build new roads around it.
   Buying the 542-acre development site and adding it to the
4,600-acre battlefield park is not an option, at least in the
Senate, Warner said.
   The mall site is currently valued at $13.5 million, but the
ultimate selling price would likely be three times higher _ a
figure approaching the federal government's annual appropriation
for park purchases.
</TEXT>
</DOC>

