<HEAD>Critics Charge VIP Riders Taking Money from Historical Programs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANASSAS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President Dan Quayle and his family
like riding government-owned horses at Manassas National
Battlefield Park, but such VIP privilege may harm the park's
historical interpretive efforts, employees say.
   Quayle and his three children _ Tucker, 15, Benjamin, 12, and
Corinne, 10 _ are regular visitors to the park, according to the
vice president's office. The family is accompanied by Secret
Services agents and local law enforcement officials.
   They ride the park's nine horses _ normally used for park
security patrols and not available for public use.
   ``You have the vice president riding U.S. government horses at a
park that is designed for historical preservation and in which the
staff is trying to control recreational use,'' said former park
historian John Hennessey, now with the New York State Division of
Parks.
   ``You have money going into maintaining these government horses
... while anyone can see the woeful condition of the rest of the
operation. What type of message does that send to the public?''
   Park Supervisor Ken Apschnikat said that while the park's horses
are not for public use, the visits by Quayle and his family are ``a
different situation'' and the use of national park facilities by
members of the executive branch is common.
   Other guest riders have included Interior Secretary Manuel Lujan
Jr., who has been riding twice, according to park spokesman Tom
Wilson.
   David Beckwith, the vice president's press secretary, said he
was unaware of complaints about the Quayles' horseback riding. ``He
enjoys it... and says it's quite beautiful,'' Beckwith said.
   Some park staff members and Hennessey, an expert on the Civil
War battles of First and Second Manassas, see the VIP trail rides
principally as a symptom of a horse program that's grown larger
than needed _ thus draining resources from interpretive services
and preservation activities.
   ``This is the worst year in the three years I've been here,''
said Ed Raus, who heads the battlefield's interpretive staff. ``We
don't have the staff to operate the programs we once did. It
definitely has been frustrating.''
   The park, site of the two Bull Run battles in which more than
22,000 soldiers died, has had to scale back its interpretive
programs.
   Raus said his department's budget has decreased from about 15
percent to 11 percent of the park's $933,000 budget this fiscal
year. The department has laid off three employees since 1988 and
suspended some bus tours and living history exhibits.
   New signs that tell the story of those who fought and died here
in July 1861 and August 1862 sit in storage, while the old system
of recorded messages that explained what occurred at specific sites
is mute.
   ``People come in and say, `we can't understand what went on,'''
said Robert E. Lee Krick, a history major working this summer as a
park interpreter. ``They ask, `Where's the bus tour from last year,
what happened to the voice boxes?'''
   In addition, battlefield sites are in need of repair.
   Apschnikat said the cutbacks stem from increases in the park's
fixed operating costs, especially salaries, coupled with a
1,200-acre expansion during the past five years.
   Park officials said it was impossible to determine the amount of
time a specific ranger or other employee might spend on a
horse-related project.
   ``You see the horse program growing and growing and growing, and
everything else going down hill,'' said park administrative officer
Jane Becker. ``You see things falling apart, you must ask where is
the money going.''
</TEXT>
