<HEAD>Hodel Only Attacks Democrats Backing Bill, Not Republicans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD KEIL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interior Secretary Donald Hodel is waging a
letter-writing campaign harshly critical of House Democrats
supporting legislation to protect a national battleground, but
Republicans backing the same bill are noticeably absent from his
target list.
   A spokesman for Hodel said Thursday that the only reason 29
Republican co-sponsors of the bill escaped his scorn is that the
targets were selected in ``haphazard'' fashion.
   Letters sent by Hodel to 13 newspapers in the home districts of
the Democrats say they should be ``ashamed'' of themselves for
backing a ``ludicrous'' plan to protect the Manassas National
Battlefield Park from nearby development.
   Hodel opposes the bill drafted by Reps. Michael Andrews,
D-Texas, and Robert Mrazek, D-N.Y., that would require the Interior
Department to acquire land now owned by a developer who plans a
shopping center, office buildings and residential units next to the
Civil War battlefield in Virginia.
   Critics say the massive development would destroy the
still-rustic feeling of the 4,600-acre battleground.
   Interior Department spokesman David Prosperi confirmed Thursday
that seven House Democrats had been singled out in letters by
Hodel, but denied that the secretary was targeting only Democrats.
   ``The selection was done in a very haphazard manner,'' Prosperi
said. ``If we had had time, we would have sent (letters) to
everyone _ Republicans and Democrats.''
   Prosperi said letters from Hodel criticizing the measure were
sent to 13 newspapers in the congressional districts of Andrews and
Mrazek, as well as Democratic Reps. John Lewis of Georgia, Bill
Richardson of New Mexico, James Clarke of North Carolina, Robert
Kastenmeier of Wisconsin, Jim Slattery of Kansas and Barbara
Kennelly of Connecticut.
   The letters were published in some of the papers in late May and
throughout June.
   In a letter to the Houston Chronicle, which appeared on May 27,
Hodel wrote: ``Andrews ought to be ashamed of himself because he is
playing politics with the future of Manassas Battlefield. It is
easy enough to grab an issue in Washington in order to gain media
attention, but the congressman's idea that the solution here is to
buy that land adjacent to the battlefield ... is ludicrous.''
   Nearly identical language, substituting only the name of the
congressman, appeared in the June 9 editions of Long Island Newsday
(published in Mrazek's district), the June 16 issues of the Atlanta
Daily World (Lewis' district), and the June 28 editions of the
Wisconsin State Journal (Kastenmeier's district).
   ``It's clear that Mr. Hodel's actions have become extremely
partisan,'' said Mrazek. ``I found the harshness of the letter
surprising.''
   While both Andrews and Mrazek were lambasted by Hodel,
Republican co-sponsors of their bill from neighboring congressional
districts escaped the interior secretary's scorn.
   Hodel favors a plan that would allow the shopping mall to be
built next to the battlefield park, but would close two roads
running through the battlefield to reduce the effect of traffic
heading to and from the complex.
   The development-control bill has 200 co-sponsors, including 29
Republicans. The Associated Press contacted 25 of the Republicans,
all of whom said newspapers in their districts had not printed
letters from Hodel.
   The letter-writing campaign especially angered Andrews, since
two Republican congressmen from districts adjacent to his Houston
district co-sponsored the legislation but were not singled out by
Hodel.
   ``Jack Fields (a Republican congressman from Houston) feels
strongly about this issue, but Hodel didn't mention him,'' Andrews
said. ``The secretary of the interior does not serve himself well
when he uses a blistering attack on people who disagree with him.
It's disappointing.''
</TEXT>
